In this markdown document, well run through a forecast using our dynamic linear models for the historical data from one NEON site, STER. We will model the ratio of bacteria and archaea (as one combined group) to fungi. Our current covariates are daily precipitation and minimum daily temperature, both averaged to the month level.

Lets look at our JAGS model code. Were including random effects for each sampling date, and fixed effects of minimum temperature and precipitation.

ourmodel <- "  model{
  
#### Priors
x[1] ~ dnorm(x_ic,tau_ic)
tau_obs ~ dgamma(a_obs,r_obs)
tau_add ~ dgamma(a_add,r_add)

#### Random Effects
  tau_alpha~dgamma(0.1,0.1)
  for(i in 1:n){                  
  alpha[i]~dnorm(0,tau_alpha)
  }

#### Fixed Effects
beta_IC~dnorm(0,0.001)
betaIntercept~dnorm(0,0.001)
betaTmin~dnorm(0,0.001)
betaPrecip~dgamma(0.01,0.01)
muTmin~dnorm(0,0.001)
muPrecip~dnorm(0,0.001)
tauTmin~dgamma(0.01,0.01)
tauPrecip~dgamma(0.01,0.01)


#### Data Model
for(t in 1:n){
OBS[t] ~ dnorm(x[t],tau_obs)
Z[t,2] ~ dnorm(muTmin,tauTmin)
Z[t,3] ~ dnorm(muPrecip,tauPrecip)
}

#### Process Model
for(t in 2:n){
mu[t] <- beta_IC*x[t-1]  + betaIntercept*Z[t,1] + betaTmin*Z[t,2] + betaPrecip*Z[t,3] + alpha[t[i]]
x[t]~dnorm(mu[t],tau_add)
}

}"

Heres the function well use for our forecast, analogous to the process model in our JAGS code. Right now we just have the precipitation driver included for the sake of developing the uncertainty analysis code - we will add Tmin back into this script later.

# our function
forecastN <- function(IC,betaIntercept,alpha,betaPrecip,beta_IC,ppt,Q=0,n=Nmc) {
  N <- matrix(NA,n,NT)  ## storage
  Nprev <- IC           ## initialize
  N[,1] <- Nprev
  for(t in 2:NT){
      mu = beta_IC*Nprev + betaIntercept*1 + betaPrecip*ppt[,t] + alpha  
      N[,t] <- rlnorm(n,log(mu),Q)  
      Nprev <- N[,t]        ## update IC
  }
  return(N)
}

plot.run <- function(ylim=c(4,31)){
  sel = seq(1,10)
  plot(time,time,type='n',ylim=ylim, ylab="N")
  ecoforecastR::ciEnvelope(time1,ci[1,sel],ci[3,sel],col=col.alpha("lightBlue",0.6))
  lines(time1,ci[2,sel],col="blue")
  points(time1,log(STER[,"ratio"]))
}

Somethings wrong. But we dont know what it is, so lets partition the variance anyways!

We dont have a random site effect because our model isnt hierarchical. Were just looking at one NEON site (STER) right now.

### calculation of variances
varI     <- apply(N.I,2,var, na.rm=T)
varIP    <- apply(N.IP,2,var, na.rm=T)
varIPD   <- apply(N.IPD,2,var, na.rm=T)
varIPDE  <- apply(N.IPDE,2,var, na.rm=T)
#varIPDEA <- apply(N.IPDEA,2,var) # we only have one site
varMat   <- rbind(varI,varIP,varIPD,varIPDE)#,varIPDEA)

## in-sample stacked area plot
V.pred.rel.in <- apply(varMat,2,function(x) {x/max(x)})
plot(time2,V.pred.rel.in[1,],ylim=c(0,1),type='n',main="Relative Variance: In-Sample",ylab="Proportion of Variance",xlab="time")
ciEnvelope(time2,rep(0,ncol(V.pred.rel.in)),V.pred.rel.in[1,],col=N.cols[1]) # IC error = black
ciEnvelope(time2,V.pred.rel.in[1,],V.pred.rel.in[2,],col=N.cols[2]) # parameter error = red
ciEnvelope(time2,V.pred.rel.in[2,],V.pred.rel.in[3,],col=N.cols[3]) # driver error = green
ciEnvelope(time2,V.pred.rel.in[3,],V.pred.rel.in[4,],col=N.cols[4]) # process error = blue
legend("topright",legend=c("Process","Driver","Parameter","InitCond"),col=rev(N.cols[-5]),lty=1,lwd=5)

We have almost no driver uncertainty, so it was too small to plot. Parameter uncertainty is large, but it is still dwarfed by process error.
